This is a feature extraction technique

Simple explanation -

PCA stands for Principal Component Analysis.

It is used when a dataset has many features.
Some of those features may carry similar information.
PCA combines that information into a smaller number of new features.

These new features are called principal components.
They keep the most important information from the original data.

So, instead of working with many columns, we can work with fewer new columns.
This makes the data easier to handle.

Benefits of PCA -

- reduces the number of features
- removes some extra or repeated information
- makes the model faster to train
- helps reduce the curse of dimensionality
- can make patterns easier to visualize
- may improve model performance in some cases

Example with features -

Suppose we are working on student data.
The dataset has these features:

- study hours per day
- attendance percentage
- test score
- assignment score
- class participation

Here, test score, assignment score, and class participation may all tell us something similar about overall academic performance.
PCA can combine this related information into one new feature, such as a principal component that represents overall performance.

So instead of using many separate columns, we can use fewer new columns that still keep most of the useful information.

Real-life analogy -

Imagine you want to describe a mango.
You can talk about its weight, size, sweetness, color, and smell.
Many of these details are connected and together describe the quality of the mango.

Instead of remembering every small detail separately, your brain may summarize them into one simple idea like "good mango quality."
PCA works in a similar way.
It takes many related features and summarizes them into a smaller number of meaningful components.

In simple words, PCA keeps the most useful parts of the data and removes less important parts.

